Need help understanding xgboost's approximate split points proposal

Ask Question
Asked 6 years, 11 months ago
Modified 1 year, 11 months ago
Viewed 5k times
This question shows research effort; it is useful and clear
16
This question does not show any research effort; it is unclear or not useful
Save this question.
Show activity on this post.

background:

in xgboost the tt iteration tries to fit a tree ftft over all nn examples which minimizes the following objective:

∑i=1n[gift(xi)+12hif2t(xi)]∑i=1n[gift(xi)+12hift2(xi)]

where gi,higi,hi are first order and second order derivatives over our previous best estimation y^y^ (from iteration t−1t−1):

  • gi=dy^l(yi,y^)gi=dy^l(yi,y^)
  • hi=d2y^l(yi,y^)hi=dy^2l(yi,y^)

and ll is our loss function.

The question (finally):

When building ftft and considering a specific feature kk in a specific split, they use the following heuristic to assess only some split candidates: They sort all examples by their xkxk, pass over the sorted list and sum their second derivative hihi. They consider a split candidate only when the sum changes more than ϵϵ. Why is that???

The explanation they give eludes me:

They claim we can rewrite the previous equation like so:

∑i=1n12hi[ft(xi)−gi/hi]2+constant∑i=1n12hi[ft(xi)−gi/hi]2+constant

and I fail to follow the algebra - can you show why is it equal?

And then they claim that "this is exactly weighted squared loss with labels gi/higi/hi and weights hihi" - a statement I agree with, but I don't understand how does it relate to the split candidate algorithm they are using...

Thanks and sorry if this is too long for this forum.

I won't go into details but the following should help you grasp the idea.

They use Quantiles (Wikipedia) to determine where to split. If you have 100 possible split points, {x1,⋯,x100}{x1,⋯,x100} (sorted), you can try the 1010-quantiles split points {x10,x20,⋯,x90}{x10,x20,⋯,x90} and have a good approximation already. This is what the ϵϵ parameter is doing. They consider a split point when the split has ∼ϵN∼ϵN more points under it than the last split point. If ϵ=0.01ϵ=0.01, you will end up with ∼100∼100 split points, being larger than {1%,2%,...,99%}{1%,2%,...,99%} of the other points. They do not consider a new split when "the sum changes more than ϵϵ" but when the number of points under the current point is larger by ϵϵ than the last one.

Now, if you have a lot of continuous points very that are already well classified, it might be useless to split between them. You want to split the parts of your data set that are very wrong, the ones that are difficult to learn. To do so, they use weighted quantiles. This is where the weights play a role. The first 1010-quantile will not be the first point that is larger than 10%10% of the points, but the first point that is larger than 10%10% of the weights.

Just adding the algebraic part to @Winks answer:

The second equation should have its sign reversed, as in:

∑i=1n12hi[ft(xi)−(−gi/hi)]2+constant=∑i=1n12hi[f2t(xi)+2ft(xi)gihi+(gi/hi)2]=∑i=1n[gift(xi)+12hif2t(xi)+gi22hi]∑i=1n12hi[ft(xi)−(−gi/hi)]2+constant=∑i=1n12hi[ft2(xi)+2ft(xi)gihi+(gi/hi)2]=∑i=1n[gift(xi)+12hift2(xi)+gi22hi]

The last term is indeed constant: remember that the gigi and hihi are determined by the previous iteration, so they're constant when trying to set ftft.

So, now we can claim "this is exactly weighted squared loss with labels −gi/hi−gi/hi and weights hihi"

Credit goes to Yaron and Avi from my team for explaining me this.

And then they claim that "this is exactly weighted squared loss with labels gi/higi/hi and weights hihi" - a statement I agree with, but I don't understand how does it relate to the split candidate algorithm they are using...

  1. If there is only one sample, and you are optimizing the ww at t−tht−th iteration, it is easy to see that the value would be w∗=−gi/hiw∗=−gi/hi, explaining (ft−−(gi/hi))2(ft−−(gi/hi))2

  2. Now you have an entire data set. In a case where the loss function has a identical second derivative, the w∗w∗ would become −avg(gi)/const−avg(gi)/const instead of −sigma(gi)/sigma(hi)−sigma(gi)/sigma(hi). I wrote it in this way because in that case, the w∗w∗ would be irrelevant to the difference of hihi among samples, since there is no difference. However, in reality, when keeping gigi unchanged, the w∗w∗ fluctuates with distribution of hihi.

I think it explains why it works as it is weighted by hihi.

I came across these equations too and tried to derive it, in addition to @ihadanny's answer:

L~(t)=∑i=1n[gift(xi)+12hif2t(xi)]=12∑i=1nhi[f2t(xi)+2gihift(xi)]=12∑i=1nhi[(ft(xi)+gihi)2−(gihi)2]=12∑i=1nhi(ft(xi)+gihi)2−12∑i=1nhi(gihi)2=12∑i=1nhi(ft(xi)+gihi)2+constantL~(t)=∑i=1n[gift(xi)+12hift2(xi)]=12∑i=1nhi[ft2(xi)+2gihift(xi)]=12∑i=1nhi[(ft(xi)+gihi)2−(gihi)2]=12∑i=1nhi(ft(xi)+gihi)2−12∑i=1nhi(gihi)2=12∑i=1nhi(ft(xi)+gihi)2+constant

Looks −gihi−gihi is a typo in the paper, it should've been gihigihi (Please let me know if I'm wrong).
